00:46:47.590 --> 00:46:51.730
of the self as something
recently that has evolved out

00:46:51.730 --> 00:46:53.810
of the Chinese
revolution, and that

00:46:53.810 --> 00:46:56.027
during the Chinese
revolution, again,

00:46:56.027 --> 00:46:58.110
we tend to think there was
a very different notion

00:46:58.110 --> 00:47:00.410
of the self and self-sacrifice.

00:47:00.410 --> 00:47:03.890
But again with the development
of capitalism in China,

00:47:03.890 --> 00:47:07.090
fairly clearly a more
Western like view

00:47:07.090 --> 00:47:12.610
of the self as something to be
enhanced, fought for, separated

00:47:12.610 --> 00:47:17.860
from society seems to have
developed very, very fully.

00:47:17.860 --> 00:47:21.630
Can you comment on sort of
more recent Chinese history

00:47:21.630 --> 00:47:25.750
and how you see these
ancient traditions,

00:47:25.750 --> 00:47:29.510
the role of the self, relating
to more modern trends in China?

00:47:29.510 --> 00:47:31.180
MICHAEL PUETT: Yes,
great question.

00:47:31.180 --> 00:47:34.680
And until recently, the
way I would have said

00:47:34.680 --> 00:47:38.050
is, sadly from my point of
view, a lot of these ideas

00:47:38.050 --> 00:47:39.070
were rejected.

00:47:39.070 --> 00:47:41.060
And what I mean by
that is the following.

00:47:41.060 --> 00:47:43.090
For much of the 20th
century, these ideas

00:47:43.090 --> 00:47:45.140
were very strongly rejected.

00:47:45.140 --> 00:47:47.360
So all the ideas I
mentioned at the beginning,

00:47:47.360 --> 00:47:51.050
that we are modern people--
and luckily for us, rejecting

00:47:51.050 --> 00:47:53.910
these traditional
ideas-- these and such

00:47:53.910 --> 00:47:57.580
a vision of a modern world
destroying a traditional world

00:47:57.580 --> 00:47:58.930
became all pervasive.

00:47:58.930 --> 00:48:01.460
And during the imperial
period, these ideas

00:48:01.460 --> 00:48:04.600
became pervasive in the world,
absolutely in China too.

00:48:04.600 --> 00:48:07.850
And you had a succession of
governments explicitly devoted

00:48:07.850 --> 00:48:10.220
to the claim, we're
going to modernize.

00:48:10.220 --> 00:48:13.270
And to modernize we're going
to destroy traditional society

00:48:13.270 --> 00:48:14.170
altogether.

00:48:14.170 --> 00:48:15.980
So texts like these were burned.

00:48:15.980 --> 00:48:18.120
The old temples were destroyed.

00:48:18.120 --> 00:48:21.150
It was an explicitly modernist
paradigm, and particularly

00:48:21.150 --> 00:48:23.730
of course under Mao, under
the Cultural Revolution,

00:48:23.730 --> 00:48:25.250
literally these
texts were burned.

00:48:25.250 --> 00:48:27.300
The idea was to
destroy the past.

00:48:27.300 --> 00:48:29.270
Then as you said
more recently, there

00:48:29.270 --> 00:48:33.910
was a reaction against Maoism
and an incredible embrace

00:48:33.910 --> 00:48:38.210
of neoliberal capitalism, much
more actually than in America.

00:48:38.210 --> 00:48:41.270
And China became a world
where sort of everything

00:48:41.270 --> 00:48:43.180
was up for sale.

00:48:43.180 --> 00:48:45.010
Everything was about
money and power.

00:48:45.010 --> 00:48:46.730
And as you said, a
vision of the self

00:48:46.730 --> 00:48:50.300
very comparable to ones
that we hold-- in fact,

00:48:50.300 --> 00:48:52.260
if anything, more extreme.

00:48:52.260 --> 00:48:53.770
Now the interesting
thing-- and I

00:48:53.770 --> 00:48:55.450
mean now meaning
the past something

00:48:55.450 --> 00:48:59.270
like eight years-- all of
this is beginning to change.

00:48:59.270 --> 00:49:01.450
And there's now a very
self-conscious debate

00:49:01.450 --> 00:49:04.580
going on in China of,
have we lost our values.

00:49:04.580 --> 00:49:08.180
Have we simply become a world
where everything comes down

00:49:08.180 --> 00:49:09.470
to money and power?

00:49:09.470 --> 00:49:12.530
And all of a sudden,
all of these old rituals

00:49:12.530 --> 00:49:13.360
are coming back.

00:49:13.360 --> 00:49:15.630
The temples are being
rebuilt. These texts

00:49:15.630 --> 00:49:17.320
are being read again.

00:49:17.320 --> 00:49:19.720
There's a huge
blogosphere in China.

00:49:19.720 --> 00:49:23.450
And now all these passages that
we've been alluding to today,

00:49:23.450 --> 00:49:25.850
they're actively being
debated and discussed

00:49:25.850 --> 00:49:27.210
in the blogosphere.

00:49:27.210 --> 00:49:29.390
And all of it is coming back.

00:49:29.390 --> 00:49:32.340
Now how this will play
out, I have no idea.

00:49:32.340 --> 00:49:35.900
But I suspect at the minimum
what's going on now--

00:49:35.900 --> 00:49:38.490
and I would put this
more globally as well--

00:49:38.490 --> 00:49:41.960
there's increasingly a view
that this one restrictive notion

00:49:41.960 --> 00:49:44.070
of the self, which really
became a global vision

00:49:44.070 --> 00:49:47.010
of the past century,
is now being questioned

00:49:47.010 --> 00:49:48.300
in a lot of quarters.

00:49:48.300 --> 00:49:50.400
And in China itself,
a lot of these ideas

00:49:50.400 --> 00:49:52.010
are actively coming back.

00:49:52.010 --> 00:49:54.400
And it's going to be, I
think, an exciting moment.

00:49:54.400 --> 00:49:56.420
Certainly in China,
but I suspect globally,

00:49:56.420 --> 00:49:59.200
when for the first time
really in a long time,

00:49:59.200 --> 00:50:01.930
the vision of the self
that's been so dominant

00:50:01.930 --> 00:50:03.630
is coming under question.

00:50:03.630 --> 00:50:05.440
And a lot of these
ideas from the past

00:50:05.440 --> 00:50:07.750
are once again being
taken seriously.

00:50:07.750 --> 00:50:10.720
And at the minimum,
this will mean

00:50:10.720 --> 00:50:12.730
another generation
will grow out not

00:50:12.730 --> 00:50:15.810
be told this vision of
the self is the right one,

00:50:15.810 --> 00:50:19.550
but actually allowed to take
from very different traditions.

00:50:19.550 --> 00:50:22.330
And the fact that this is going
on yet again finally in China

00:50:22.330 --> 00:50:25.124
as well is something I think
it incredibly exciting.

